 :tx/rationale "WITNESS ARCHITECTURE DEEP ANALYSIS: THE SEMANTIC PAIRING PROBLEM. \n\nTHE GAP: 272 invariants exist. 1,386 tests exist. 32 witnesses exist. The tests DO test the invariants — but the system can't PROVE which test covers which invariant.\n\nWHY: The witness system (INV-WITNESS-001..011) requires EXPLICIT pairing: a Falsification-Bound Witness (FBW) links one INV entity to one test function with a verification depth. The trace scanner finds 464 spec-entity references across 84 source files (90% coverage). But references in doc comments (// INV-STORE-001: ...) are DOCUMENTATION, not test evidence. promote_tests_to_l2 only handles Kani proofs and Stateright models with HARDCODED binding tables.\n\nTHE REAL PROBLEM: This is an OBSERVATION-PROJECTION DUALITY gap at the verification layer. The tests are OBSERVATIONS of invariant behavior. The witnesses are PROJECTIONS of those observations onto the spec graph. The gap between 1,386 tests and 32 witnesses is the round-trip error of the verification projection.\n\nTHREE APPROACHES TO CLOSE THE GAP:\n\nAPPROACH A — NAME-BASED MATCHING (simple, partial): Test functions that contain an INV ID in their name or body are automatically paired. Example: test_merge_is_commutative contains 'INV-MERGE-001' in a comment → auto-witness. Coverage: maybe 10-20% of tests name their INV explicitly. Effort: extend scan_source to extract test-level INV refs (it already extracts module-level ones).\n\nAPPROACH B — SEMANTIC MATCHING (medium, good coverage): For each INV, extract the falsification condition (a natural language description of what would violate it). For each test, extract the assertion pattern (what the test actually checks). Use string similarity / keyword overlap to SUGGEST pairings. Present to the agent for confirmation. Coverage: 40-60% with good false-positive rate. Effort: moderate — bag-of-words similarity is ~50 LOC.\n\nAPPROACH C — THE ACQUISITION FUNCTION SOLUTION (deep, correct): A witness pairing IS a recommendation. The system recommends 'test T likely witnesses INV I.' The recommendation has an expected_delta_fs (how much F(S) improves if the pairing is confirmed), a cost (agent attention tokens to review the pairing), and an alpha. The hypothesis ledger tracks which recommended pairings the agent confirmed vs rejected. Over time, the system learns which test patterns correspond to which invariant patterns. THIS IS UAQ APPLIED TO WITNESS COVERAGE. The witness gap isn't a special problem — it's another instance of the universal acquisition function selecting the highest-value information to present. The 'information' is a proposed witness pairing. The 'cost' is the review overhead. The 'alpha' is the expected F(S) improvement from confirmed coverage.\n\nRECOMMENDATION: Approach A first (immediate, low effort, closes ~20% of gap). Then Approach C as part of UAQ (the correct general solution). Approach B is superseded by C.\n\nSPEC: INV-WITNESS-011 (every current-stage INV must have L2+), ADR-FOUNDATION-025 (UAQ)."
